I began ingesting Domino's pizza regularly in the late 70's. The Time's have changed and trends in pizza have changed, and Domino's has tried to evolve along with our tastes, sometimes more successfully than other times.  The dough  has enough gluten, but not too much. Those of you who have bought high quality 00 high gluten flour from Italy, cold aged in the refrigerator to make pizza noted the incomparable taste, but at the cost of a some GI distress in digesting the high gluten flour. I also haven't detected the effects of baking powder, which transform me into an Orca with a bloated belly.  The sauces, especially the Marinara are to my liking and I always order extra. Too much sugar or high fructose sweeteners are the bane of commercial pizza sauces, the Domino's sauces are not overly sweet. The ingredients seem fresh and are sprinkled on in the correct proportions for taste.  An interesting option is the gluten free pizza, and in this case a gluten free and even a dairy free (cheese less) pizza can be had. Family members who are gluten intolerant and dairy intolerant or with allergies can now enjoy their pizza alongside the rest of the family. Now Domino's can make gluten free pizza cheese-less pizza almost as good as the home made pizzas crafted by this old pizza chef.  Domino's  picked up fresh and hot, not 15 minutes after the pizza craving hits. That's hard to beat.
